American democracy posed by the politicisation of conservative Protestantism; and the likely impact on democratic development of the global expansion of Pentecostalism. The author draws out several common themes from the analysis of these case studies, the most important of which is the ‘liberal-democracy paradox’. This ensures that there will always be tensions between faiths that proclaim some notion of absolute truth and political orders that are rooted in the idea of compromise, negotiation and bargaining. Written in an accessible style, this book will appeal to students of politics, sociology and religion, and prove useful on a range of advanced undergraduate and postgraduate courses.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDemocracyxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / History & Theory.2bisacsh  aAmerican democracy.  aChristian traditions.  aPentecostalism.  aabsolute truth.  aconservative Protestantism.  ademocratisation.  adevelopment of democracy.  aliberal-democracy paradox.  apolitical order.  apoliticisation.1 aAnderson, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978184779261740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781847792617423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781847792617/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles